"I don't think the UN intends to cooperate with terrorists, but they have
to reevaluate the whole situation," he said.
In Jerusalem, the Israeli foreign ministry assailed the UN report for
making no mention of the use by Hezbollah guerrillas of UN compounds in
southern Lebanon as shields for launching rocket and mortar attacks
against Israeli targets.
UN spokeswoman Sylvana Foa earlier Thursday refused to be drawn on
Israeli criticism of the UN report, and said the United Nations was now
looking to the future concerning peace prospects.
